{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"07a8cac1-b6ea-4007-acc9-788475159557","content":"Here's a step-by-step diagnostic and fix plan:\n\n---\n\n## Phase 1 — Diagnose\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Check which SDKs are installed\ndotnet --list-sdks\n\n# 2. Check current workload state (look for version mismatches)\ndotnet workload list\n\n# 3. Check which workload manifests the new SDK expects\ndotnet workload search maui\n\n# 4. Inspect the actual build error (capture full output)\ndotnet build YourApp.csproj -v diag > build-diag.log 2>&1\n```\n\nLook for these red flags:\n- **\"Workload … is not installed\"** → manifests are stale.\n- **\"Android SDK not found\"** or **missing `platforms;android-XX`** → Android SDK out of sync.\n- **Multiple SDK versions** listed → `global.json` may pin you to the wrong one.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 2 — Fix workloads\n\n`dotnet workload update` **is safe** — it updates manifests *and* installed workload packs to match the SDK you're running. It doesn't touch other SDK bands.\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Run from an elevated (admin) terminal\ndotnet workload update\n\n# 2. If that still errors, do a clean reinstall of the MAUI workload\ndotnet workload install maui --force\n\n# 3. Verify\ndotnet workload list\n#    Should show: maui, android, ios, etc. with matching SDK version\n```\n\n> **Tip:** If you have a `global.json` pinning a feature band (e.g. `8.0.100`), either remove it or update it to the new band (e.g. `9.0.100`). Workloads are resolved per feature band.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 3 — Fix Android SDK\n\nWorkload update installs the .NET Android bindings but **not** the platform tools/build-tools themselves. If you still see Android SDK errors:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Find where your Android SDK lives\n#    Default: %LOCALAPPDATA%\\Android\\Sdk\n#    Or check VS: Tools → Options → Xamarin → Android Settings\n\n# 2. Accept licenses and install required components\n#    (adjust the path to your sdkmanager)\n& \"$env:LOCALAPPDATA\\Android\\Sdk\\cmdline-tools\\latest\\bin\\sdkmanager.bat\" --licenses\n& \"$env:LOCALAPPDATA\\Android\\Sdk\\cmdline-tools\\latest\\bin\\sdkmanager.bat\" `\n    \"platforms;android-35\" \"build-tools;35.0.0\" \"platform-tools\"\n\n# 3. Ensure ANDROID_HOME is set correctly\n[System.Environment]::SetEnvironmentVariable(\"ANDROID_HOME\",\n    \"$env:LOCALAPPDATA\\Android\\Sdk\", \"User\")\n```\n\nCheck your `.csproj` for `<SupportedOSPlatformVersion>` and `<TargetPlatformVersion>` — make sure the android API level matches what you just installed.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 4 — Validate\n\n```powershell\n# Clean rebuild\ndotnet clean\ndotnet build -c Debug\n\n# If it targets Android specifically:\ndotnet build -c Debug -f net9.0-android\n```\n\n---\n\n### Quick summary of what's safe\n\n| Command | Safe? | What it does |\n|---|---|---|\n| `dotnet workload update` | ✅ | Updates manifests + packs for your current SDK band |\n| `dotnet workload install maui --force` | ✅ | Reinstalls; fixes corrupted state |\n| `sdkmanager --licenses` | ✅ | Accepts Google license prompts |\n| Deleting `global.json` | ⚠️ | Safe if you want the latest SDK; review first |","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"de113f12-51f2-4cf7-aafb-3107cc59156f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The working directory is empty - there's no repository content to explore. The user is asking for a general diagnostic and fix plan for .NET MAUI build issues after SDK upgrade. I should provide a comprehensive plan based on my knowledge of .NET MAUI, workloads, and Android SDK management.","outputTokens":1006,"requestId":"9540:41C1F:15CA478:18352F6:6A0671E8"},"id":"67bccee3-d6e2-4635-802a-3ab5e0f223b0","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:08:13.305Z","parentId":"5a7019f9-b456-4f54-9998-079f7c60e741"}
